  						<table border='0' cellpadding='3' cellspacing='0' width='92%'>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%' bgcolor='#0E024D' class='spti2' align='center'>EVERQUEST : HIS RISE - CHAPTER 4</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	  <td width='100%'><font face='verdana' size='2pt'><center><b>Chapter Four</b><br><i>Calm. Pain. History.</i></center><p>
     Men cheered and whooped as Ebon came into the fray, slashing the gnolls in whatever spot was open.  Behind him, stood Tonmerk a man who many probably did not recognize, except for various veterans, and when they did see him they uttered prayers to Nife.  As most of the other Steel Warriors came up to the front, the paladin’s began reciting prayers and casting various spells upon themselves.  It was then, when magic hit.<p>
     Noxious gases filled the gates, they smelled of something dead, and when breathed it poisoned.  Many of the militia as well as the gnolls fell, at this, a retreat was made back further into the city.  Ebon motioned to Tonmerk to begin the healing process, but even before the warrior motioned anything, the high priest was already doing his job.  Ebon chuckled at trying to let a high priest know his role.<p>
     Yet, someone else was healing as well.  Ebon quickly turned himself, shifting his gaze from one section to the other, to find the other healer.  After a moment, he found the source, it was Rusty.  The halfling’s pupil, Ebon scoffed at the idea of the druid in battle, but could not deny him that his aid would help.<p>
     "Rusty! Start sending swarms at them, we have enough healing here.  Go offensive boy!", shouted Ebon across the inner section, about a block away from the front gates.<p> 
     Dorson halted his castings, offensive.  He needed to go offensive, he hadn’t casted an offensive spell since the days he was the plains of Karana, and only under the watch of his mentors.  Never had he attacked anything that would truly put up a fight back, his heart pounded against his chest, as his stomach began to burn.  Dor turned to look at Ebon, who still had his eyes on him, with the knowing look of ‘get on it already’.<p>
        Dor turned to face the gnolls, it was a brief moment of respite, as the gases began to finally clear up, yet now, the center leading gnolls were being sent in.  Dor began his gestures, dark swirls of crud began to form around his moving hands as he recited the spell, already gnolls began to take notice of the man in tight leather armor.  The spell released, and sent the closest gnoll into a fit of screaming pain as a mud like substance began to creep up his body, burning his fur and flesh away as it crept further toward its head.<p>
     At that sight, the gnolls zeroed in on one target, the caster.  The sight of six gnolls charging for him sent him almost into a panic.  His head searched for another spell, something that would affect most all.  He spoke a few quick words and motioned a simple gesture, on the last word, a brilliant flare shot out from his hands and hit the on coming gnolls.  Slowly, they halted their run and slowed down to a walk.  Moving with their arms in front of them, unable to see.<p>
     One, however, came to his sense quicker and resumed his charge towards the druid.  Dor looked over at the warriors, who were moving towards him and the blinded gnolls.  Quickly, Dor reached into the air and cried out an incantation, with a huge force a gust of wind blew in front of him, hitting the gnoll square in the chest.  The air gust sent him flying backwards to the others, that when their comrade knocked into them, two fell and one lashed out and sliced the throat of the other.  Dor smiled to himself, happy with himself that he had remained somewhat calm through the on coming attacks.<p>
     As the warriors saw the druid send the gnoll, that was after him, flying they turned towards the gnolls who were still blinded, now assisted by others within the Tesch Clan.  Once again, the clash of steel filled the air, and Dor realized he was way too close to the main fray than he should be, and retreated back towards the small entrance before the pond.<p> 
     As he stood glancing at the area about him, gathering a position to assist his sister city in battle, he screamed.  Pain shot into his mind, as his eyes began to see things blur and twist into a chaotic mess of colors, his mind plunged into some flux of chaos.  Without a struggle, the druid fell to his knees swaying slightly, as his head surged with utter torment.<p>
     Within him, he felt as if he was swimming in lake of fire.  That burned his flesh as he swam, but as hard as he tried to swim to the surface, he found none.  The druid’s form was unable to breath, and began to gag for breath.  Just before he decided to give up and let the lake burn him alive, a soothing feeling swept over him.  As the cold rush hit him, he gasped for air, opening his eyes wide, only to see the forms of Camlend and Ebon before him.<p>
     Dor blinked a little, letting small streaks of once tears continue down their given paths along his cheeks.  Dor looked at the hands of Camlend and noticed they still shimmered with a cool white light, at the sight the druid looked up to the paladin with a pained look.  The paladin in turn, just smiled at the young Dorson.<p>
     "So, is he gonna to be alright?", Ebon queried the paladin, a second before he lifted his head to look at the gnoll forces, now in full numbers pouring into the city.<p>
     Camlend turned his head up from the druid and looked in the same direction as Ebon, and replied that the boy would be fine, before he turned his head back down to Dorson.<p>
     "Dorson, head over to the Hall of Sorcery the adepts there should provide better protection than anything," Camlend halted his words for another trumpet to blast, signaling another retreat. "perhaps, we too will be joining you soon."  At those words, he gave the druid a grin and stood following Ebon, who was already trotting back into the battle.<p>
     Dorson lifted his eyes up and saw them all.  Hundreds of gnolls were in the streets, at this point, thunder crackled in the air as spells began to be casted on a more frequent bases.  Mages from the Hall had finally saw the need to assist the warriors and sent in some of their own.  Enchanters stood along the walls casting spells that resisted the gnoll’s magic.  The entire city was covered in the white and yellowish haze of magic.<p>  
     Buildings burned, sending large pillars of smoke into the air.  Local’s were trying to extinguish the flames, but their efforts often ended with their deaths to a spell or blade of the gnolls.  Dor glanced about, trying to regain his position.  During the attack made on him, he had been moved from the pond and now sat next to the town’s clock.  He knew where the Hall was from here, standing he had started to walk in that direction when a voice caught his attention, a whisper.<p>
     "Rusty, I wouldn’t suggest going to the Hall of casters." an unseen voice said, yet it did not sound like the last unseen voice he had heard earlier.<p>
     "Simonic?" Dor whispered to the air, turning around knowing he wouldn’t see anyone.<p>
     "Ah, you’ve met him too have you?", from next to the shadow of the clock, a form stepped out.  It was a half elven male, from his appearance Dor couldn’t really place an age on him but could tell many ladies would enjoy a night with him, if they hadn’t already.<p>
     The elf had brown eyes and matching brown hair.  Yet, they seemed to fit utterly well on him, with his soft tipped nose and the elven ears.  The elf smiled and motioned the druid to follow him.  Dor turned and saw the little half elf run across the court yard and dodged between buildings.  It wasn’t until he stuck his head out from around a corner and motioned Dor again that he began to follow.<p>
     Through the city they ran, dodging men running towards the battle.  Even from this far into the city, crashes and explosions were clearly heard.  Every so often, the hairs on the head of the druid and half elf raised as a large electrical charge bolted throughout the city.  As buildings passed by, Dor began to realize where they were headed.  The docks.<p>
  As the half elf reached the docks, he jumped down to the shore below, motioning for the druid to do the same.  As Dor hit the ground, the half elf looked him over and grinned.<p>
     "Well, perhaps I should tell ya who just asked you to follow, to what could have been your death.  I’m Tiethroe, just Tiethroe, personal scout of Ebon Strongbear," at his introduction he lifted two menacing looking daggers from his belt and gave an almost funny bow.  At the bow a smile spread across Dor’s lips.  "Alright, so I’m not good at formal greetings, but at least I give it an effort."<p>
     "I’m Dorson Refron, Pupil of Truven, and -- ", in mid sentence Tiethroe cut him off.<p>
     "That’s great Rusty, and please don’t bow, specially not to a rogue," Tiethroe looked around as he spoke, and found a small log over beneath the pier and headed over there "now, why did I bring you here you’re asking, well it’s quiet simple."<p>
     Tiethroe walked over next to the log and inspected it for water logging and insects a moment before he sat down.  An awkward smile spread across his face, only to have the log a moment later fall over to the side, along with Tiethroe.  His arms flailed as if trying to dodge an attack or to grab on to something.<p>
     At the sight, Dor burst into a laughing fit as he stood just watching the spectacle.  As he laughed, Tiethroe cursed out various words until he realized how it must have looked and then he too began to laugh.  After he had gained enough composure from laughing, he readjusted himself, and sat on the fallen log holding his legs out in the soft sand to keep from rolling back or forward.<p>
    "Well, I did not bring you here to watch me fall, but to keep you safe," the half elf explained this as he was dusting off the wet dirt on his stained leather armor.<p>
     "Camlend said I would be safe at the Hall of Sorcery," Dor glanced around underneath the dock area and concluded," and this Tiethroe, I hope is not the Hall of Sorcery"<p>
     A grin spread across Tiethroe’s face, an almost childlike grin.  "Of course it’s the Hall, and I’m the grand wizard -- just don’t ask me to cast any spells, they’re all parlor tricks."<p>
     Dor could see that Tiethroe found this little gag almost outright funny, as he tried to hide the laughter from his own joke.  Dor, however, did not view the situation as humorous as did the scout.<p>
     "Ah, well, sorry.  I brought you here because I don’t think you would be able to survive the attack upon the Hall.  Earlier, I had went out and snuck around the Gnoll’s, it wasn’t until a minor mishap on my part that I was discovered.  Sekerv, too, was with me, but they didn’t catch him till he started to save me.  At least, I think he was with me," Tiethroe seemed to be thinking a moment before he shrugged and continued.<p>
     "Well, I know enough of the gnoll’s language to pick up most of the things they spoke of, and their plan is to raid the Hall of Sorcery, within this city and retrieve spells which open gates to Erudin.  They spoke of some powerful magics, I assume even though I know very little of magic.  I’m not too sure Ebon and them know the power they wield, they had an ancient looking book that they had wrapped in leathers, because when they touched it, pain creased their faces and their hands began to smoke,<p>
     "I’m not sure what it was, but they casted a few spells from that book and they were of the likes I had never seen.  I guess they plan on going to Erudin, the capital of the humanoid’s magic, and try and retrieve spells and tomes there.  Though, I am not certain.  Actually, the ones who had carried the leather wrapped book, left the company and spoke something of the EverFrost Peaks."<p>
     A concerned expression went over the rogue’s face, as he tried to figure out what their need in EverFrost was.  An almost empty wasteland of freezing snow and old ruins.  Ruins.  Were they after something hidden within the ruins, or after something hidden within the rives.  Dor, who was still standing and listening, was still trying to put things together in his own head.  Both, didn’t seem to get too far.<p>
     "They are after the great lich Miragul," the voice spoken was above them, on top of the docks.  Immediately both human and half elf, went utterly silent, even holding their breaths.<p>
      Footsteps could be heard on the decks, until it reached the edge of the docks and took a step off. Landing firmly on his feet, dressed in now red robes, was Simonic, the traveling mage.  Both Dor and Tiethroe’s eyes met, and both sighed in unison.  A smile spread across Dor’s lips, as Tiethroe began to ask the questions.<p>
      "You know what they are doing?", Tiethroe inquired the mage, still standing where he had jumped off from the docks.<p>
      "I don’t know ‘what’ they are doing, but I presume what they are going to do," at this, Sim pulled a small chunk of some animal from his pouch and spoke a few words, in a moment air wiped around him, granting him flight into the air.  Smiling contently, he sat down on a cushion of air.<p>
     "Well, mage, what are they going to do?" the half elf asked, now standing from his own log, and took up a spot leaning against one of the pillars holding the dock up.<p>
     "Well, rogue, that book which burned, is known as the Tome of Diz’Urian, or once commonly known as ‘Tome of Life’, but plays far more giving life to the dead and not healing or granting life to the living.  It’s necromancy at it’s fullest."  Sim, still resting, turned his hazel gaze over to Dor, who was standing along the wall, hidden next to the shadows.<p>
      Dor caught his eyes, and felt as if he should ask his question now.  "Where would the gnolls get a book of such power?"<p>
     Sim grinned at the question, and seemed to enjoy giving the answer.<p>
     "The Tome of Diz’Urian, was an ancient tome which surfaced during the Combine Empire.  Keep in mind, that even during the reign of the Empire, necromancy within it’s walls was forbidden.  It was written in the blood of a great Combine wizard known as Serivok, and after he wrote the book took the surname of Diz’Urian, betraying houses name<p>
     "During the time of the High Combine Council, they ordained that the tome be destroyed and Serivok entombed within a Crystal of Death.  These, crystals, were more of a prison in modern terms, yet to escape it was next to impossible.  In the crystal he would age and soon come to a point and die, yet that never occured,<p>
     "At the hearing of his crimes against the Empire, for practicing the art’s of necromancy," at this point, Sim seemed to drift into a different time and his voice began almost ragged and sinister, "yet, more than just his crimes can into play, as he betrayed many within the Empire.  Anger erupted throughout the walls of the Council, magic of every elements flew, burning everything in it’s path,<p>
     "From here, the entire council was slain, and personal Empire portals, portals used to get to one kingdom to the other, erupted.  Exploding with sheer and utter power that sunk many of them deep into the ground’s of Norrath.  Thus, was the fall of the Combine Empire, and of their many relics."  Sim seemed to end here, within his tale of the history behind the book.  His hazel eyes seemed to burn as he stared into nothing.<p>
     Tiethroe, stood straighter taking his back off the poll and began to speak of the tale, "So, the great empire fell because of this mage, Serivok and his book?"<p>
     Simonic nodded and added, "Very few people know of how the Combine Empire was started, but some do and understand.  The forgers of the Empire, were selected men, Barbarians.  Selected by the gods to protect the lands of Norrath, to keep order so they themselves would not have to intervene.  These barbarians were transformed under the touch of the gods, and became what we call now ‘humans’.<p>
     "Why, would just a normal wizard, be put into a prison, when they could have just killed him then?"  This question, came from Dor as he walked closer to Tiethroe.<p>
     "Good question, and simple answer.  He was the Grand High Protector of the Empire.  An extremely high title, and one that comes with a lot of power and influence.  When it was discovered that he was practicing necromancy, he was taken into custody.  Understand, that taking a Protector into custody is no simple task.  For the Protectors, were the original forgers.  Thus, the Crystal of Death was used to trap them for almost eternity."<p>
     Dor and Tiethroe stood thinking of what they heard, slowly Tiethroe began to sit down on the dirt, silent.  Tiethroe appeared to be either thinking or just now becoming bored.  Then Dor thought of another question.<p>
     "That still doesn’t explain why they would goto Miragul."<p>
      Simonic continued to bob up and down on his cushion of air, and thought for a bit.  "Miragul, now a lich, was the greatest necromancy to live previous to Serivok.  Even those within the walls of Neriak aren’t as skilled and powerful as Miragul once was.  It may be, that the gnolls wish to resurrect the lich, and aid them in other necromatic spells.  Here, I am not sure.  But, bad things lie ahead."<p>										
<center>**********************************************<p>
<b>Chapter Five</b><br><i>The Hall. Portals. Liches.</i></center><p>
     As if those words seemed to be a cue, a huge explosion followed.  Magic burned the air, swirls of crimson fire seemed to cry as they reached upwards for the cool night sky.  Cries of men and gnoll’s were drowned out by the fierce rage of powerful magics.  Barks of spells were heard, and the loud clanking of running steel boots.  They had reached the Hall.<p>
<center><b><i>...more to come...</b></i></center>
